<HEADLINE>
<P>
PREP BASKETBALL TODAY'S GAMES; 
</P>
<P>
BOYS, GIRLS CHAMPIONS TO BE CROWNED 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By LONNIE WHITE, TIMES STAFF WRITER 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Eight Southern California Regional high school basketball titles will be 
decided today, with the winners advancing to the State championship games next 
week. 
</P>
<P>
The boys' and girls' Division II and III games will be played at the Sports 
Arena, with the first game at 9:30 a.m. Division IV and V games will be played 
at Cal State Dominguez Hills, beginning at 2:30 p.m. 
</P>
<P>
In the boys' Division II title game, defending Southern Regional champion 
Glendora (28-5), which won the Southern Section 4-AA Division title last week, 
will meet Artesia (27-2), the 4-A Division champion at 3:30 p.m. In the 
Division III matchup, Goleta Dos Pueblos (18-13) will play Anaheim Servite 
(19-11) at 11:30 a.m. 
</P>
<P>
In the girls' Division II game, Pasadena Muir (28-5) will meet San Diego Point 
Loma (29-3) at 1:30 p.m. The Division III final is a rematch of the Southern 
Section 3-AA Division final between Brea-Olinda (32-0) and Palos Verdes (29-5) 
at 9:30 a.m. 
</P>
<P>
The four games at Cal State Dominguez Hills: Strathmore (24-2) vs. 
</P>
<P>
Rosamond (20-7) in the girls' Division V game at 2:30 p.m.; Faith Baptist 
(21-10) vs. El Cajon Christian (18-11) in the boys' Division V final at 4:30 
p.m.; Santa Maria St. Joseph (27-3) vs. Tollhouse Sierra (27-1) in the girls' 
Division IV final at 6:30 p.m., and Oxnard Santa Clara (26-0) vs. Santa Maria 
St. Joseph (22-7) in the boys' Division IV final at 8:30 p.m. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> LA031090-0029 </DOCNO>
<DOCID> 187394 </DOCID>
<DATE>
<P>
March 10, 1990, Saturday, Home Edition 
</P>
</DATE>
<SECTION>
<P>
Sports; Part C; Page 13; Column 1; Sports Desk 
</P>
</SECTION>
<LENGTH>
<P>
318 words 
</P>
</LENGTH>
<HEADLINE>
<P>
LATE BASKET BEATS LONG BEACH POLY 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By LONNIE WHITE, TIMES STAFF WRITER 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
For the first 30 minutes of the Southern California Regional Division I 
championship game Friday night, Santa Ana Mater Dei guard Jason Quinn wasn't a 
factor, but he finished the game a star. 
</P>
<P>
With Mater Dei trailing, 45-43, and 1.8 seconds remaining, Quinn made a 
desperation, 20-foot three-point basket to give the Monarchs a 46-45 victory 
over Long Beach Poly before a crowd of 5,071 at the Sports Arena. 
</P>
<P>
Poly, which made only two of six free throws in the last three minutes of the 
game, had a chance to increase its lead to three points after center Willie 
McGinest made a free throw with 19.3 seconds remaining. 
</P>
<P>
However, McGinnest missed the second and Mater Dei got the rebound. With less 
than five seconds remaining, Quinn found himself trapped on the baseline in the 
right corner and put up the winning shot that hit nothing but net. 
</P>
<P>
"I had no idea that I'd make it. . . It was just a Hail Mary," said Quinn, who 
finished with 10 points, including eight in the game's final two minutes. "I 
threw it up and just tried to get fouled." 
</P>
<P>
Quinn, who was fouled on the play but missed the free throw, sent Mater Dei 
(31-1) into its first State title game since 1987, when it defeated Ygnacio 
Valley, 69-51. 
</P>
<P>
In the first half, Mater Dei's pressure defense caused problems for Poly's 
half-court offense. During one stretch, the Jackrabbits failed to score a point 
in over six minutes as the Monarchs took a 14-8 lead early in the second 
quarter. 
</P>
<P>
In the fourth quarter, Poly, which outrebounded the Monarchs, 35-30, began to 
dominate the boards. Scoring mainly on second shots, the Jackrabbits opened a 
44-40 lead with :50 seconds left in the game. 
</P>
<P>
But Quinn made his first of two fourth quarter three-point shots to cut the 
lead to one, setting up the dramatic finish. 
</P>
<P>
"Stuff like this happens," Poly Coach Ron Palmer said. "It is all apart of the 
game. We'll get our share down the line." 
</P>
</TEXT>
