<P>
THE CAT IN MAINE IS MAINLY IN THE DRAIN 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By Associated Press 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
<P>
SCARBOROUGH, Me. 
</P>
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Tootsie the cat is back home after spending five weeks in a storm drain. 
</P>
<P>
"The poor little thing looked awful when we got her out. 
</P>
<P>
She was just skin and bones," said Nicole Lonsdale, who helped find the cat for 
her neighbors, Peter and Teri Tyson. 
</P>
<P>
Tootsie disappeared on Jan. 26, after apparently entering an open storm drain 
that was later sealed off by a snow plow clearing roads in this southern Maine 
city. 
</P>
<P>
The Tysons and neighbors searched the area but gave up hope of finding the 
6-year-old cat. 
</P>
<P>
Then, late last week, Tyson was chatting with Lonsdale in her driveway when he 
heard a faint meow from the nearby drain. He pried the lid off and climbed 
inside, calling Tootsie's name. The cat poked its head out of a pipe and 
scampered to Tyson. 
</P>
