</SECTION>
<LENGTH>
<P>
76 words 
</P>
</LENGTH>
<HEADLINE>
<P>
BRIEFLY 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
From Times Staff and Wire Reports 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Stake Increased: General Automation, the struggling Anaheim computer vendor, 
said Thursday that Sanderson Electronics PLC of the United Kingdom has 
increased its stake in the firm from 35% to 49%. Sanderson exercised warrants 
and loan conversion rights it received when it agreed to provide up to $4 
million in financing to General Automation in December, 1988. General 
Automation has recently begun to turn a small profit after years of heavy 
losses. 
</P>
</TEXT>
<TYPE>
<P>
Column; Brief 
</P>
</TYPE>
<SUBJECT>
<P>
GENERAL AUTOMATION INC; COMPUTER INDUSTRY; SANDERSON ELECTRONICS PLC; 
ACQUISITIONS; SECURITIES 
</P>
</SUBJECT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> LA031090-0151 </DOCNO>
<DOCID> 188213 </DOCID>
<DATE>
<P>
March 10, 1990, Saturday, Orange County Edition 
</P>
</DATE>
<SECTION>
<P>
Business; Part D; Page 2; Column 1; Financial Desk 
</P>
</SECTION>
<LENGTH>
<P>
104 words 
</P>
</LENGTH>
<HEADLINE>
<P>
BRIEFLY 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
From Times Staff and Wire Reports 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Westport Savings Seized: Federal thrift regulators seized Westport Savings Bank 
on Friday and put it in receivership, saying it was insolvent. 
</P>
<P>
Its assets of $163 million were transferred to a newly created thrift called 
Westport Federal Savings Bank, which was put under control of the Resolution 
Trust Corp. In 1984, a group of South Orange County investors bought Westport, 
which had opened in Hanford in 1979, and moved its headquarters to Mission 
Viejo. The group later opened a branch in Laguna Beach. After a change in 
directorship more than a year ago, the thrift moved its headquarters back to 
Hanford. 
</P>
</TEXT>
<TYPE>
<P>
Column; Brief 
</P>
</TYPE>
